    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (76.26) and **Junior Caminero** (74.22) serving as our offensive pillars. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from an elite matchup against a struggling starter with a 7.83 xERA, and his dynamic platoon advantage provides a massive boost to his floor despite his lower batting order. Meanwhile, **Junior Caminero** occupies a prime #2 hole and enjoys a strong SP skill advantage, making him our most reliable engine for R and RBI production. While **Kazuma Okamoto** (61.18) carries a strong score due to a favorable park and opposing starter skill, he is tasked with navigating a neutral platoon, though his spot in the heart of the order keeps his value high.\n\nWe are exercising caution with several high-upside assets due to external variables. **Trea Turner** (54.95) and **Kyle Schwarber** (51.19) remain in the lineup despite a 40% rain risk, though their scores are tempered by a matchup against Logan Webb and the slow delivery speed that mitigates **Trea Turner**'s stolen base upside. The most difficult personnel decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, whose score of 39.79 fell just short of our 40.0 floor; the rain risk coupled with a tough matchup against Casey Lawrence pushed him to the bench in favor of safer, higher-floor options like **Carson Benge**.\n\nFinally, we must note the status of the roster deeper down the depth chart. **Yordan Alvarez** has been removed from consideration entirely due to a postponement, and we continue to monitor **Zac Veen** as he remains in the minors with the Albuquerque Isotopes. We are also keeping a close eye on the late-pending lineups for **Gary Sanchez** and **Colt Keith**; should their projected spots shift significantly against their respective starters, we may see further fluctuations in their efficiency scores. The objective remains to protect our game caps while squeezing every point of efficiency out of our speed-heavy core.",
